#!CSeaGreen #!N  #!Rall656 Light Objects #!N #!EC #!N #!N A 
Light Object is used to place a light in a scene 
for the renderer. Lights can be either local or distant. Local 
lights have a position and a color. Distant lights are at 
infinity, and have a direction and a color. It is often 
not necessary to specify a light in a scene because the 
renderer has a default built-in light that is sufficient for most 
purposes. For ambient lights, only  #!F-adobe-times-bold-r-normal--18*   color #!EF can be specified, 
not  #!F-adobe-times-bold-r-normal--18*   direction #!EF or  #!F-adobe-times-bold-r-normal--18*   position #!EF . For  #!F-adobe-times-bold-r-normal--18*   
distant #!EF lights, the  #!F-adobe-times-bold-r-normal--18*   direction #!EF can be absolute, or 
it can be relative to the current location of the camera, 
as specified in a  #!F-adobe-times-bold-r-normal--18*   'from camera' #!EF clause. #!CForestGreen #!N 
#!N  #!F-adobe-courier-bold-r-normal--18*   #!T,72,252 #!N  #!F-adobe-times-bold-r-normal--18*   object #!EF TAB  #!F-adobe-times-bold-i-normal--18*   number #!EF 
